Implemented Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js project.

## Changes Made:

### 1. Installed @vercel/analytics package
- Added `@vercel/analytics` as a dependency to package.json
- Used npm to install the package, updating package-lock.json

### 2. Integrated Analytics component into the application
- Modified: `app/layout.tsx`
  - Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from '@vercel/analytics/next';`
  - Added `<Analytics />` component to the body of the root layout
  - Placed the Analytics component after {children} as per Next.js App Router best practices

### Implementation Details:

The integration follows the official Vercel Analytics documentation for Next.js App Router:
- Fetched latest instructions from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart
- Added the Analytics component to the root layout file (app/layout.tsx)
- Preserved existing code structure and styling
- Maintained proper TypeScript types and imports

### Framework Details:

This is a Next.js 16.2.6 project using:
- App Router architecture
- TypeScript
- React 19.2.4

### Verification:

✓ ESLint passed with no errors on the modified file
✓ Package installation completed successfully
✓ Lock file (package-lock.json) updated with new dependency
✗ Build fails due to pre-existing Supabase configuration issue (not related to Analytics)

Note: The build failure is due to missing Supabase environment variables (`supabaseUrl is required`), which is a pre-existing issue unrelated to the Analytics integration. The Analytics code itself is correctly implemented and will work once the project is properly configured with Supabase credentials.

### Next Steps for User:

To enable Web Analytics on Vercel:
1. Deploy the project to Vercel
2. Navigate to the Analytics section in your Vercel dashboard
3. Click "Enable" to activate Web Analytics for this project
4. Analytics will automatically start collecting pageview data

The implementation is complete and ready for deployment.
